from sklearn.datasets import load_breast_cancer
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
data = load_breast_cancer()

# Create a DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(data.data, columns=data.feature_names)

# Add the target column
df['target'] = data.target

# Display the first few rows of the DataFrame

Question 2

In [4]:
# Visualize feature distributions
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 14))
df.drop(columns=['target']).hist(figsize=(18, 14), bins=30, edgecolor='black')
plt.suptitle('Feature Distributions', fontsize=16)
plt.show()

# Compute correlation matrix
corr_matrix = df.corr()

# Plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 12))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap='coolwarm', linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Feature Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()

<Figure size 1800x1400 with 0 Axes>

Based on the heatmap values (looking for the highest correlation values compared to the target) and the distributions (looking for data representing something close to a normal distrubution) we think that the mean radius, mean perimeter, worst concave points, mean concave points, and worst radius would make for effective features for classification.

# Identify top correlated features with target
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif
corr_target = corr_matrix['target'].drop('target').abs().sort_values(ascending=False)
print("Top correlated features with target:")
print(corr_target.head(10))

# Select top 5 features using SelectKBest
X = df.drop(columns=['target'])
y = df['target']
selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=5)
X_new = selector.fit_transform(X, y)
selected_features = X.columns[selector.get_support()]
print("Top 5 features selected using SelectKBest:", selected_features)

# Identify top correlated features with target
from sklearn.feature_selection import SequentialFeatureSelector
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
corr_target = corr_matrix['target'].drop('target').abs().sort_values(ascending=False)
print("Top correlated features with target:")
print(corr_target.head(10))

# Select top 5 features using SequentialFeatureSelector
X = df.drop(columns=['target'])
y = df['target']
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=10000)
sfs = SequentialFeatureSelector(model, n_features_to_select=5, direction='forward')
X_new = sfs.fit_transform(X, y)
selected_features = X.columns[sfs.get_support()]
print("Top 5 features selected using SequentialFeatureSelector:", selected_features)

Question 5

In [7]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
# Estimate feature relevance using Random Forest Classifier
X = df.drop(columns=['target'])
y = df['target']
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_model.fit(X, y)
feature_importances = pd.Series(rf_model.feature_importances_, index=X.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)
print("Feature importance estimated using RandomForestClassifier:")
print(feature_importances.head(10))

Feature importance estimated using RandomForestClassifier:

In [23]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Select top and bottom 5 features
top_5_features = feature_importances.head(5).index.tolist()
bottom_5_features = feature_importances.tail(5).index.tolist()

# Train and evaluate models using Random Forest classification for top 5 features, as previously displayed in Question 5
X_top = df[top_5_features]
X_train_top, X_test_top, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_top, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
rf_model_top = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_model_top.fit(X_train_top, y_train)
y_pred_top = rf_model_top.predict(X_test_top)
top_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_top)
print(f"Classification accuracy with top 5 features: {top_accuracy:.4f}")

# Train and evaluate models using Random Forest classification for bottom 5 features, as previously displayed in Question 5
X_bottom = df[bottom_5_features]
X_train_bottom, X_test_bottom, _, _ = train_test_split(X_bottom, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
rf_model_bottom = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_model_bottom.fit(X_train_bottom, y_train)
y_pred_bottom = rf_model_bottom.predict(X_test_bottom)
bottom_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_bottom)
print(f"Classification accuracy with bottom 5 features: {bottom_accuracy:.4f}")
print("Top 5 Feature Accuracy:", top_5_features)
print("Bottom 5 Feature Accuracy:", bottom_5_features)

Classification accuracy with top 5 features: 0.9561
Classification accuracy with bottom 5 features: 0.7982
Top 5 Feature Accuracy: ['worst area', 'worst concave points', 'mean concave points', 'worst radius', 'worst perimeter']
Bottom 5 Feature Accuracy: ['concave points error', 'texture error', 'symmetry error', 'mean symmetry', 'mean fractal dimension']

As you can see our predictions matched up fairly well to what the outputs were from our models and filters used.
